[1] Monsoon related diarrhea - Nepal
Date: Tue 19 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OneWorld South Asia [edited]
<http://southasia.oneworld.net/article/view/90185/1/>

Monsoon fuels diarrhea in Nepal, 80 dead
---------------------------------------------
The onset of the monsoon in Nepal has triggered an outbreak of acute
diarrheal diseases (ADD) that have killed over 80 people, and infected 10
000, in remote rural areas with meager medical facilities. Since telephone
connections with most of the 24 affected districts have been disrupted,
following the destruction of communication infrastructure and health posts
by Maoist guerrillas, ministry of health officials fear the death toll from
ADDs could be higher.
Dr. Mahendra Bahadur Bista, the director of the epidemiology and disease
control division of the ministry, says that "compared to the previous 2
years, the situation now is alarming." He feels an early monsoon, and the
lack of safe drinking water, is fueling the spread of the disease. Since 40
percent of Nepal's population lacks access to drinking water, and over 70
percent does not have safe drinking water, the rainy season is usually
accompanied by an outbreak of diarrhea. Even Nepal's capital, Kathmandu, is
not spared from contaminated drinking water, and a subsequent diarrhea
outbreak, every year.
A recent study, by the epidemiology and disease control division, disclosed
that water supplied to Kathmandu contained several pollutants, including
coliform bacteria.
In 2001, there were 8836 cases of diarrhea and 247 fatalities. According to
the division, there were 7300 cases, with 150 deaths, recorded in 2002. In
2004, the toll is likely to rise, with 80 deaths already recorded by the
middle of the monsoon season.
Nepal saw one of the worst outbreaks of diarrhea in 1991, when 91 584 cases
were reported, with 1795 deaths. The outbreak season ranges from April to
the end of September each year.
ADDs hit Kathmandu at the end of May in 2004, affecting over 5000 persons
in a week's time. With the extension of the monsoon, the epidemic is
gradually moving to rural areas. Officials at the ministry expect the toll
will rise, since over a dozen districts, in Nepal's eastern and central
regions, have been badly affected by the floods, with people ingesting
contaminated drinking water there.
Although the disease is spreading to other parts of the country, most of
the fatalities occurred in 5 remote districts of far-western and
mid-western Nepal.
Predictably, the worst affected districts of Achham, Baitadi, Kalikot,
Dang, and Jajarkot are also the most poverty-stricken. According to the
National Planning Commission, over 72 percent of the population in these
areas lives below poverty line, or, has a daily income of USD 1.
Both the Sukraraj Hospital and Kanti Children Hospital, Nepal's only
children's hospital, are overflowing with diarrhea patients. A spokesman
for Kanti reveals, "we, daily, admit 10-15 children suffering from
diarrhea-related diseases. Our past experiences have shown the pressure
will continue till the end of September 2004."
--
