[2] Diarrhea & Cholera - Philippines (Pangasinan)
Date: Mon 18 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manila Bulletin OnLine [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/PROV2004071814319.html>

After SARS scare, cholera outbreak stalks Pangasinan
-----------------------------------------------
After the scare caused by Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) almost 2
years ago [2003] (referring to an incident in April 2003, when an Overseas
Filipino Worker (OFW) from Canada, vacationing in Barangay, died of SARS,
which she contracted in Toronto), Pangasinan is in trouble again, as
another disease, cholera, stalks the province, said Department of Health
(DoH) Region One Director Eduardo Janairo, in a talk to newsmen last Thu 15
Jul 2004. But Janairo quickly said that it seems that not only Pangasinan
is in trouble with cholera, but, also, the whole Philippines "as we are now
noted internationally to have cholera."
Janairo said that the World Health Organization (WHO) demanded the
reporting of cholera cases in the Philippines, adding that WHO is now
helping the Philippines stop cholera through donations of some equipment
and facilities. "This is a bad, very bad impression again on the
Philippines. Now, it [has] affected our lives, not only as a person.
Politically and economically, it has affected us," he said.
Janairo recalled that the cholera outbreak started on 31 May 2004, in
Malasiqui, then spread to Calasiao, Basista, Urbiztondo, Sta. Barbara,
Binmaley, Bugallon, Mangaldan, San Fabian, and San Carlos City. To date, of
the 2055 reported cases of gastroenteritis in all of the affected towns and
cities of Pangasinan, 81 were confirmed cholera cases.
San Carlos appeared to be the worst affected, accounting for 654 cases and
7 deaths. Of the cases, some 45 were confirmed to be cholera. Janairo said
Pangasinan was a potential area for cholera, because, in a survey conducted
in early 2000 by the DoH, only 75 percent of the population had been found
using water-sealed toilets, and, only 75 percent had been using a potable
water supply.
Last year's [2003] statistics showed 85 percent were found utilizing
potable water and 85 percent utilizing water-sealed toilets
--
