[3] Cholera - Pakistan (Khuzdar)
Date: Mon 11 Jul 2004
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@ntlworld.com>
Source: Daily Times [edited]
<http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_11-7-2004_pg7_4>

Death toll from dirty water reaches 12 in Khuzdar
-----------------------------------------------
The death toll from contaminated water has risen to 12 in Wadh, in Khuzdar
district.
Patients complaining of gastroenteritis have been admitted to district
headquarters hospital. Many of them were reported to be in critical
condition. It is feared that the toll might rise, because the hospital is
inadequately equipped, with both medicines and staff, to treat the patients.
Wadh residents said they were forced to drink contaminated water from
ponds, because the area is facing a severe drought this summer [2004]. They
complained about a lack of medicines in the hospital, and, alleged that the
district government had not taken any steps to help the victims.
Balochistan Chief Minister Jam Muhammad Yousaf has directed the district
administration to ensure that patients were treated properly. The Khuzdar
district coordination officer, and the Health Department officials, visited
the area, and, directed the local administration to provide prompt medical
treatment to the victims. Officials said potable water was being supplied
to the people of the area and samples of contaminated water had been taken
to laboratories. They said food was also being supplied to drought-affected
people.
Mr. Yousaf has expressed concern about deaths from contaminated water and
warned the authorities to not be lax in helping the victims.
--
